emale":"1329–Zesnulá","1330–Male":"1330–Zesnulý","1332–Female":"1332–Zesnulá","1335–Female":"1335–Zesnulá","1337–Male":"1337–Zesnulý","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1352–1420":"1352–1420","1354–1385":"1354–1385","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1310–1388":"1310–1388","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1361":"1361","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","26 November 1352":"26. listopadu 1352","22 JUN 1960":"22. června 1960","1335":"1335","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1310":"1310","1420":"1420","1332":"1332","1342":"1342","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","Surrey, England":"Surrey, Anglie","Youlston, Devon, England":"Youlston, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Winkleigh, Devon, England, England, United Kingdom":"Winkleigh, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1335–":"1335–Afdød","1327–Female":"1327–Afdød","1329–Female":"1329–Afdød","1330–Male":"1330–Afdød","1332–Female":"1332–Afdød","1335–Female":"1335–Afdød","1337–Male":"1337–Afdød","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1352–1420":"1352–1420","1354–1385":"1354–1385","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1310–1388":"1310–1388","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1361":"1361","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","26 November 1352":"26. november 1352","22 JUN 1960":"22. juni 1960","1335":"1335","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1310":"1310","1420":"1420","1332":"1332","1342":"1342","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Youlston, Devon, England":"Youlston, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Winkleigh, Devon, England, England, United Kingdom":"Winkleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1335–":"1335–Overleden","1327–Female":"1327–Overleden","1329–Female":"1329–Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1332–Female":"1332–Overleden","1335–Female":"1335–Overleden","1337–Male":"1337–Overleden","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1352–1420":"1352–1420","1354–1385":"1354–1385","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1310–1388":"1310–1388","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1361":"1361","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","26 November 1352":"26 november 1352","22 JUN 1960":"22 juni 1960","1335":"1335","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1310":"1310","1420":"1420","1332":"1332","1342":"1342","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Youlston, Devon, England":"Youlston, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Winkleigh, Devon, England, England, United Kingdom":"Winkleigh, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1335–":"1335–Deceased","1327–Female":"1327–Deceased","1329–Female":"1329–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1332–Female":"1332–Deceased","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","1337–Male":"1337–Deceased","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1352–1420":"1352–1420","1354–1385":"1354–1385","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1310–1388":"1310–1388","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1361":"1361","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","26 November 1352":"26 November 1352","22 JUN 1960":"22 June 1960","1335":"1335","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1310":"1310","1420":"1420","1332":"1332","1342":"1342","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Youlston, Devon, England":"Youlston, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Winkleigh, Devon, England, England, United Kingdom":"Winkleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Beaumont was born in 1335, in Youlston, Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John Beaumont, was 26 and her mother, Alice Scudamore, was 25. She had at leas